## Checklist before moving to Day 2

- [ ] `docker-compose up` (or local Postgres) has 9 databases created, one per service naming convention (`auth_service_db`, etc.)
- [ ] Config Server starts and serves `/auth-service/default` successfully
- [ ] Eureka dashboard shows `config-server` registered (once it points at Eureka)
- [ ] API Gateway starts, registers with Eureka, and rejects an unauthenticated request to a protected route with 401
- [ ] Auth Service starts, registers with Eureka, and you can `POST /api/auth/register` + `POST /api/auth/login` through the Gateway and get a real JWT back
- [ ] `GET /internal/auth/users/{id}` works when called directly (not through the Gateway) — this is what Customer Service will Feign-call on Day 2

Once this checklist passes, Day 2 (Customer, Restaurant, Menu Services) will introduce the first real Feign client — `CustomerServiceClient` calling `GET /internal/auth/users/{id}` to validate a `user_id` at registration. The Day 2 guide will open with the OpenFeign conventions (package layout, fallback pattern, timeout config) that every subsequent service's Feign client should follow.
